{"add":{"doc":{"id":"8f2c73de63364e2862f82868ab632e2ce59065671521c2556dc42150a9daa78a","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Chaucer_Hoccleve.png/300px-Chaucer_Hoccleve.png","previous":[],"after":["Chaucer wrote in continental accentual-syllabic meter, a style which had developed since around the 12th century as an alternative to the alliterative Anglo-Saxon metre.[19] Chaucer is known for metrical innovation, inventing the rhyme royal, and he was one of the first English poets to use the five-stress line, a decasyllabic cousin to the iambic pentameter, in his work, with only a few anonymous short works using it before him.[20] The arrangement of these five-stress lines into rhyming couplets, first seen in his The Legend of Good Women, was used in much of his later work and became one of the standard poetic forms in English. His early influence as a satirist is also important, with the common humorous device, the funny accent of a regional dialect, apparently making its first appearance in The Reeve's Tale."]}}}